    <article class="content-article">
      <p>Nine times out of ten, when someone calls about their LG dryer not heating, they tell me the same thing: 'It was working fine yesterday, now my clothes come out cold and damp.' The good news is most LG heating problems have the same handful of causes, and we can usually get you back to dry clothes the same day.</p>

      <h2>Why Your LG Dryer Stopped Heating: Top 5 Causes</h2>
      <p>In my fifteen years fixing dryers, I've seen the same culprits over and over. The heating element burns out first — especially on older DLGX and DLEX models. You'll hear the dryer running normally, but zero heat comes out. Second is a blown thermal fuse, usually because the lint trap hasn't been cleaned in months. Third, the high-limit thermostat fails and cuts power to prevent overheating. Fourth issue is a bad cycling thermostat that can't regulate temperature properly. Finally, control board problems show up on newer ThinQ models where the smart features interfere with basic heating cycles.</p>

      <h3>Heating Element Failure Signs</h3>
      <p>When the heating element goes bad, you'll notice the drum spins and air moves, but clothes stay damp even after a full cycle. Most homeowners don't realize the element can partially fail too — giving you weak heat that takes forever to dry anything.</p>

      <h3>Thermal Fuse Problems</h3>
      <p>A blown thermal fuse is like a safety switch that's done its job. Once it trips, your dryer won't heat until we replace it. The fuse itself costs under ten dollars, but finding why it blew prevents the same failure next week.</p>

      <h2>Step-by-Step Troubleshooting for LG Dryer Heating Issues</h2>
      <p>Before calling for service, check your lint trap and the exhaust vent outside your house. I've driven to Pasadena homes where a simple cleaning fixed the 'broken' dryer. Next, run an empty cycle on high heat and feel for warm air at the exhaust. No heat means electrical issues. Weak heat suggests airflow problems or a dying heating element. Listen for unusual sounds — clicking often means a bad relay, while grinding points to drum problems affecting airflow. Check your circuit breaker too. LG dryers need 240 volts, and a tripped breaker cuts that to 120, giving you spin but no heat.</p>

      <h3>What You Can Safely Check</h3>
      <p>Clean the lint trap completely, including the screen edges where buildup hides. Check that the exhaust vent outside isn't blocked by birds, lint, or debris. Make sure the dryer door closes firmly — a loose latch prevents heating on most LG models.</p>

      <h3>When to Stop DIY Troubleshooting</h3>
      <p>Don't remove the back panel or mess with electrical connections. One wrong move with 240 volts can kill you. If basic cleaning doesn't restore heat, call us rather than risk electrocution or fire.</p>

      <h2>How to Test Your LG Dryer's Heating Element</h2>
      <p>Testing a heating element requires a multimeter and working around live electrical connections. Most homeowners don't have the tools or experience to do this safely. The element sits behind the dryer's back panel, connected to high-voltage wires that stay energized even when the unit's unplugged — you have to kill power at the breaker. We test for continuity across the element and check resistance values against LG's specifications. A reading of infinity means the element's open and needs replacement. But here's what the DIY videos don't tell you: even a good reading doesn't guarantee the element works under load.</p>

      <h3>Why Professional Testing Matters</h3>
      <p>Elements can test fine with a meter but still fail when they heat up. We use load testing that simulates real operating conditions. Plus, replacing an element means disconnecting gas lines on gas models — definitely not a DIY job.</p>

      <h3>Signs You Need Professional Help</h3>
      <p>If you're not comfortable working with electrical panels and 240-volt circuits, call us. We carry OEM heating elements for all LG series and can swap them out in about thirty minutes once we confirm the diagnosis.</p>

      <h2>When to Replace vs Repair Your LG Dryer</h2>
      <p>Age matters more than anything else. If your LG dryer is under five years old, repair almost always makes sense. The heating element costs around $200 to replace including labor, versus $800 or more for a comparable new dryer. But once you hit eight or ten years, especially on basic models, multiple failures start piling up. I've seen Burbank customers spend $400 fixing heating issues, only to have the control board die two months later. On newer Signature and ThinQ models, repair makes sense even at seven or eight years because replacement costs run $1,200 and up.</p>

      <h3>Cost-Effective Repair Scenarios</h3>
      <p>Single component failures like heating elements, thermal fuses, or thermostats are worth fixing regardless of age. These parts fail from normal wear, not because the whole machine is dying.</p>

      <h3>When Replacement Makes More Sense</h3>
      <p>Multiple simultaneous failures, especially involving the drum, transmission, or control electronics, usually mean it's time to shop for a new dryer. We'll give you an honest assessment rather than sell unnecessary repairs.</p>

      <h2>Preventing Future LG Dryer Heating Problems</h2>
      <p>Clean your lint trap after every single load — not just when it looks full. Lint buildup restricts airflow, making your heating element work harder and burn out faster. Check the exhaust vent outside quarterly, especially if you have a long vent run. In LA's dusty climate, external vents clog faster than you'd expect. Have the internal ductwork cleaned annually if you do more than eight loads per week. Don't overload the dryer or run multiple consecutive loads without breaks. The heating system needs cool-down time, especially during summer months when ambient temperatures spike.</p>

      <h3>Maintenance That Actually Works</h3>
      <p>Use the moisture sensor cycles instead of timed dry. Overdrying stresses the heating element and wastes energy. Replace flexible transition ducts every few years — they collect lint inside the ridges where you can't clean.</p>

      <h3>Warning Signs to Watch For</h3>
      <p>Longer dry times, clothes coming out hotter than normal, or burning smells during operation all signal developing problems. Catching issues early usually means cheaper repairs.</p>

      <h2>Safety Precautions Before Diagnosing Dryer Problems</h2>
      <p>Never work on a dryer that's plugged in, even if it's turned off. The heating element and related circuits carry 240 volts that can kill instantly. Turn off the circuit breaker, not just the dryer switch. Gas dryers add explosion risk — if you smell gas at all, evacuate and call the gas company before calling us. Don't use makeshift tools or bypass safety switches to 'test' components. I've seen house fires started by homeowners who jumped thermal fuses or overrode door latches. Lint is incredibly flammable, and electrical sparks from amateur wiring attempts have burned down houses.</p>

      <h3>What Never to Attempt Yourself</h3>
      <p>Heating element replacement involves high-voltage connections that can arc and cause fires. Gas valve work requires licensed technicians — there's no DIY exception. Control board replacement often requires programming that needs factory software.</p>

      <h3>When to Call Emergency Services</h3>
      <p>Gas smells, burning odors during operation, sparks, or any visible damage to electrical cords means stop using the dryer immediately and call for professional help.</p>

      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <h3>Why is my LG dryer running but not heating up?</h3>
      <p>Most of the time it's a blown thermal fuse or bad heating element. The thermal fuse is a safety device that cuts power when the dryer overheats — usually from a clogged lint trap or blocked exhaust vent. Once it blows, you get drum rotation and airflow but zero heat. The heating element itself can burn out from normal wear, especially on dryers over five years old. We can test both components and get you heating again same day.</p>

      <h3>How much does it cost to fix an LG dryer that won't heat?</h3>
      <p>Depends what's actually broken. A thermal fuse runs about $120 total including our service call. Heating element replacement costs around $200 for the part and labor. Thermostats are usually $150 to replace. Control board issues run $300-400. The $65 diagnostic fee gets waived when you approve the repair, so you're only paying for parts and labor. We'll give you the exact cost upfront before starting any work.</p>

      <h3>Can I fix my LG dryer heating problem myself?</h3>
      <p>I wouldn't recommend it. These machines use 240-volt circuits that can kill you instantly if you touch the wrong wire. Plus, gas models have explosion risks if you mess with the burner assembly. About the only thing safe to try yourself is cleaning the lint trap and checking the outside exhaust vent. Beyond that, you're risking electrocution, fire, or gas leaks. The money you save on DIY isn't worth dying over.</p>

      <h3>How long should an LG dryer heating element last?</h3>
      <p>In my experience, most LG heating elements last six to eight years with normal use. Heavy use households — families doing ten or more loads per week — might see failure around five years. Neglected maintenance shortens element life significantly. If you never clean the lint trap or exhaust vent, expect heating problems within three or four years. The newer Signature models seem to last a bit longer, but they're also more expensive to replace when they do fail.</p>

      <h3>What are the signs that my LG dryer heating element is bad?</h3>
      <p>The obvious sign is clothes staying damp after a full cycle, but you might notice longer dry times first. The dryer runs normally — drum spins, air moves, timer advances — but little or no heat comes out the exhaust. Sometimes elements fail partially, giving you weak heat that takes forever to dry anything. You won't hear unusual noises with element failure, unlike belt or motor problems. If you're getting some heat but not enough, that's usually a dying element on its way out.</p>

